article.description:
Margo Dydek and Lindsay 
Whalen each scored 16 points as the Connecticut Sun downed the
Minnesota Lynx, 79-62.
article.headline: Whalen, Dydek fuel Sun's victory over Lynx
article.linkText: Whalen, Dydek fuel Sun's victory over Lynx
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Lindsay Whalen and Margo Dydek scored
16 points each to lead the Connecticut Sun to a 79-62 victory over
the Minnesota Lynx on Thursday night.

Asjha Jones came off the bench to score 13 points and pull down
a season-high 11 rebounds for the Eastern Conference-leading Sun
(9-3).

"One of the things we really expressed to Asjha in the
offseason was to improve her rebounding," Sun coach Mike Thibault
said. "Every time she gets a double-figure rebounding game it's a
huge plus."

Katie Douglas added 12 points and seven rebounds while drawing
the assignment of defending Minnesota's rookie sensation Seimone
Augustus, who scored 15 points. It matched her second-lowest
scoring total of the season and was eight points below her season
average.

"That's what Katie is known for," Minnesota coach Suzie
McConnell Serio said. "As soon as the shot goes up she's finding
Seimone and not finding the basketball. She's trying to make it
very difficult and not give her easy looks. We, at times, played
into their hands and allowed her to take Seimone away."

Nicole Ohlde led the Lynx with 16 points and seven rebounds.

The Sun pulled away late by outscoring the Lynx 39-22 over the
final 14:52. But it was a different story in the first half after
the Lynx (5-7) opened the game with a 9-2 run and the Sun responded
with a 14-0 spurt. The teams traded runs the rest of the half and
the Sun led 34-28 at the break.

Minnesota battled back to tie the game at 40 with 5:10 left in
the third quarter, but a Taj McWilliams-Franklin jumper with 4:52
left in the quarter started an 11-0 run that put the Sun ahead for
good.

"That's one of the things about our team is when we get on a
roll we seem to have some long runs in us," Thibault said. "I
think part of that is our conditioning. I think part of that is
because we keep playing at that fast pace. Teams that tend to walk
it up can't get long runs because they don't take advantage of the
little breaks that you can get or make for yourself with transition
basketball."

Dydek also had seven rebounds and four blocks, while Whalen
grabbed six rebounds. McWilliams-Franklin added eight points and 10
rebounds. The Sun outrebounded the Lynx 50-31.

"Getting outrebounded 50-31 makes all the difference in the
world," McConnell Serio said. "We started out strong and made
runs at them in the second half, but they are very talented. They
have weapons inside and out. They got baskets when they needed to
and contained penetration into the paint. They made it very
difficult."

Nursing a variety of minor injuries, including back spasms,
Nykesha Sales, the Sun's second-leading scorer at 16 points per
game, was held scoreless for three-plus quarters before scoring
five straight points midway through the fourth quarter.
